Here are top 10 security monitoring use cases for File Share Servers such as Windows File Servers, SMB shares, DFS shares, or NAS-backed shares.

#	Security Monitoring Use Case	What to Detect	Why It Matters
1	Mass File Deletion	A user or process deleting many files within a short time	Could indicate ransomware, insider threat, or accidental bulk deletion
2	Mass File Modification / Encryption Behavior	Many files renamed, modified, or extensions changed rapidly	Strong indicator of ransomware activity
3	Unauthorized Access to Sensitive Shares	Access attempts to finance, HR, legal, backup, or admin shares by unauthorized users	Helps detect privilege abuse or compromised accounts
4	Failed Access Attempts to File Shares	Repeated failed access attempts on SMB shares	May indicate brute-force attempts, misused credentials, or reconnaissance
5	Permission Changes on Shares or Folders	ACL changes, new users/groups added, Everyone/Authenticated Users granted access	Prevents privilege escalation and accidental exposure
6	Access Outside Business Hours	File access, copy, delete, or permission changes during unusual hours	Useful for detecting compromised accounts or insider activity
7	Large Data Copy or Exfiltration	Large volume of files copied, downloaded, or read by one user/system	Could indicate data theft or compromised endpoint activity
8	Access from Unusual Source Systems	File share access from unknown servers, workstations, VPN IPs, or non-standard locations	Helps detect lateral movement or unauthorized systems
9	Admin Share Access Monitoring	Access to C$, D$, ADMIN$, hidden shares, or management shares	Attackers often use admin shares for lateral movement
10	Service Account Misuse	Interactive logon, unusual file access, or permission changes by service accounts	Service accounts are high-value targets and should have predictable behavior

For a strong monitoring design, I would prioritize these first:

High priority

Mass file modification or encryption behavior
Mass deletion
Permission changes
Large data copy or exfiltration
Admin share access

Useful log sources

Windows Security Event Logs
File Share Auditing
Object Access Auditing
Sysmon, if deployed
Microsoft Defender for Endpoint
Microsoft Sentinel or Splunk
Storage/NAS audit logs
Active Directory logs
VPN and firewall logs

Example detection logic:

Trigger alert when:
A single user modifies, renames, or deletes more than 500 files
within 10 minutes
on a sensitive file share.

Example alert name:

Possible ransomware activity on file share server

Recommended alert severity:

Use Case	Severity
Mass encryption/modification	Critical
Mass deletion	High/Critical
Permission change on sensitive share	High
Large data copy	High
Failed access attempts	Medium
Access outside business hours	Medium
Admin share access	Medium/High
Service account misuse	High
