Below is a practical implementation approach.

1. Enable Windows audit policies

On the file share server, enable these audit policies using Group Policy.

Go to:

Computer Configuration
 -> Windows Settings
 -> Security Settings
 -> Advanced Audit Policy Configuration
 -> Audit Policies

Enable these:

Audit Policy	Enable
Audit File System	Success and Failure
Audit File Share	Success and Failure
Audit Detailed File Share	Success and Failure
Audit Handle Manipulation	Success and Failure
Audit Logon	Success and Failure
Audit Account Logon	Success and Failure
Audit Security Group Management	Success and Failure
Audit Authorization Policy Change	Success and Failure

You can also configure using PowerShell:

auditpol /set /subcategory:"File System" /success:enable /failure:enable
auditpol /set /subcategory:"File Share" /success:enable /failure:enable
auditpol /set /subcategory:"Detailed File Share" /success:enable /failure:enable
auditpol /set /subcategory:"Handle Manipulation" /success:enable /failure:enable
auditpol /set /subcategory:"Logon" /success:enable /failure:enable
auditpol /set /subcategory:"Account Logon" /success:enable /failure:enable
auditpol /set /subcategory:"Security Group Management" /success:enable /failure:enable
auditpol /set /subcategory:"Authorization Policy Change" /success:enable /failure:enable

Verify:

auditpol /get /category:*
2. Enable auditing on the actual shared folders

This is very important. Enabling audit policy alone is not enough. You must also configure auditing on the folders you want to monitor.

Example folder:

D:\Shares\Finance
D:\Shares\HR
D:\Shares\Legal
D:\Shares\Projects

Go to:

Folder Properties
 -> Security
 -> Advanced
 -> Auditing
 -> Add

Add auditing for relevant users/groups, for example:

Everyone
Authenticated Users
Domain Users

But for production, avoid auditing everything everywhere. Start with sensitive shares.

Recommended auditing permissions:

Action	Audit
Read data / List folder	Success and Failure
Create files / Write data	Success and Failure
Delete	Success and Failure
Delete subfolders and files	Success and Failure
Change permissions	Success and Failure
Take ownership	Success and Failure

For ransomware and insider-threat monitoring, at minimum audit:

Write
Delete
Change permissions
Take ownership
